{"code":"import pynwb
import h5py
import remfile
from dandi.dandiapi import DandiAPIClient

# Access remote NWB file
client = DandiAPIClient()
dandiset = client.get_dandiset("001375", "0.250406.1855")
asset = next(dandiset.get_assets_by_glob("sub-MS13B/sub-MS13B_ses-20240725T190000_ecephys.nwb"))
remote_file = remfile.File(asset.download_url)
h5_file = h5py.File(remote_file, 'r')
io = pynwb.NWBHDF5IO(file=h5_file, load_namespaces=True)
nwb = io.read()

# Extract general info
info = {
    "Session description": nwb.session_description,
    "Session start time": str(nwb.session_start_time),
    "Subject ID": nwb.subject.subject_id,
    "Subject sex": nwb.subject.sex,
    "Subject species": nwb.subject.species,
    "Subject age": nwb.subject.age,
    "Subject description": nwb.subject.description,
}

# Number of electrodes, units, trials
n_electrodes = nwb.electrodes.shape[0]
n_units = nwb.units.shape[0]
n_trials = nwb.trials.shape[0]

info["Number of electrodes"] = n_electrodes
info["Number of units"] = n_units
info["Number of trials"] = n_trials

# Preview a few trial start/stop times (first 5)
trials_df = nwb.trials.to_dataframe().head()

# Preview a few units (first 5 spike times per unit)
units_df = nwb.units.to_dataframe().head()

print("Session and Subject Info:")
for k, v in info.items():
    print(f"{k}: {v}")
print("\nFirst 5 trials:")
print(trials_df)
print("\nFirst 5 units (truncated):")
print(units_df)
","reasoning":"Demonstrate how to extract and display the basic session, subject, trial, and unit information for orientation and reproducibility in a Jupyter notebook."}

# Get unit and trial dataframes

trials_df = nwb.trials.to_dataframe()

# 2. Distribution of trial durations
trial_durations = trials_df['stop_time'] - trials_df['start_time']
plt.subplot(1,2,2)
plt.hist(trial_durations, bins=30, color='skyblue', edgecolor='k')
plt.xlabel('Trial Duration (s)')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.title('Distribution of Trial Durations')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()","reasoning":"Visualize high-level features of the dataset to help users understand the structure of neural and behavioral data with summary plots for spike counts and trial durations."}

trial_durations = (trials_df['stop_time'] - trials_df['start_time']).values[:20]

# Align spikes to trial start, for trials in the first 30s window for clarity
peri_spike_times = []
for t_start, t_dur in zip(trial_starts, trial_durations):
    rel_spikes = spike_times[(spike_times >= t_start) & (spike_times <= t_start+t_dur)] - t_start
    peri_spike_times.append(rel_spikes)

# Plot raster (trial-aligned)
plt.figure(figsize=(9, 5))
for i, spikes in enumerate(peri_spike_times):
    plt.vlines(spikes, i+0.5, i+1.5)
plt.xlabel('Time from trial start (s)')
plt.ylabel('Trial')
plt.title(f'Spike Raster (Unit {unit_id}) Aligned to Trial Start (first 20 trials)')
plt.xlim(0, np.max(trial_durations))
plt.show()","reasoning":"Demonstrate how to align and visualize spike trains to trial events, setting up downstream analyses such as perievent or peristimulus time histograms."}
